**Prehistory (Before 3500 BCE)**

* Emergence of Homo sapiens in Africa (~300,000 BCE)
* Development of stone tools and early agriculture (~10,000 BCE)
* Neolithic Revolution: transition from nomadic hunter-gatherers to settled agricultural societies (~10,000 - 4,000 BCE)

**Ancient Civilizations (3500 BCE - 500 CE)**

* Mesopotamia (Sumerians, Akkadians, Babylonians): invented writing (cuneiform), created cities, and developed governance systems (3500 BCE - 539 CE)
* Ancient Egypt: pyramids, mummification, hieroglyphics, and pharaonic dynasties (3100 BCE - 30 BCE)
* Indus Valley Civilization (Harappans): sophisticated urban planning, architecture, and water management (3300 BCE - 1300 BCE)
* Ancient China: development of writing, philosophy (Confucius, Taoism), and imperial dynasties (1600 BCE - 220 CE)
* Classical Greece: birthplace of democracy, theater, and philosophy (Socrates, Plato, Aristotle) (8th century - 146 CE)
* Ancient Rome: expansion of empire, law, governance, and architecture (27 BCE - 476 CE)

**Middle Ages (500 CE - 1500 CE)**

* Fall of the Roman Empire and rise of feudalism in Europe (5th - 15th centuries)
* Islamic Golden Age: cultural, scientific, and philosophical advancements (8th - 13th centuries)
* Byzantine Empire: continuation of Roman Empire in Eastern Europe (395 - 1453 CE)
* Medieval Europe: knights, castles, and the rise of nation-states (10th - 15th centuries)

**Early Modern Period (1500 CE - 1800 CE)**

* Renaissance: artistic, scientific, and intellectual revival in Europe (14th - 17th centuries)
* Age of Exploration: European discovery and colonization of the Americas (15th - 16th centuries)
* Enlightenment: emphasis on reason, individual rights, and democratic principles (17th - 18th centuries)
* Industrial Revolution: transformation of manufacturing and society with new technologies ( late 18th - early 19th centuries)

**Modern Era (1800 CE - present)**

* Nationalism and imperialism: rise of modern nation-states and empires (late 19th - early 20th centuries)
* World Wars I and II: global conflicts shaping international relations and geopolitics (1914-1918, 1939-1945)
* Cold War: ideological rivalry between capitalism and communism (1945-1991)
* Globalization: increasing interconnectedness of economies, cultures, and societies (late 20th century - present)

This is just a brief overview of the major milestones in human civilization's history.
